results.notes:
Here is Oluna’s description that goes with this herbarium specimen.
By: Oluna & Adolf Ceska (aceska@telus.net) 2021-01-31 17:58:46 PST (-0800)
Cap: 11.2 cm in diameter, smooth. The center of the cap is yellowish-brown, changing towards the margin to pink; in places on the very edge with red short lines, the centre also minutely areolated (cracked).
Stipe: 9 cm long, 3.5 cm at the apex, narrowed in the middle, towards the base swollen to 3.5 cm; stipe bright yellow with obscure reticulation at the apex. Stipe has a reddish band around the base, and the base is narrowed, +/- pointed; the point is dark brown.
Tubes: ca. 2.5 cm long, olive-yellow; the surface of the pores pocketed; pores small, round, staining blue when bruised.
Flesh: firm, dense-bright-yellow, esp. in the stipe; when cut longitudinally, the flesh is at first pale-yellow in both cap and stipe; flesh in the cap starts to blue quickly, first at the base of pores and then the blue is spreading through the whole flesh of the cap; the stipe gets intense-yellow, especially on sides; the pores start blueing when the flesh of the cap is loosing its blue colour and is fading. Flesh in the base has a band of yellow-brown that turns in to reddish-brown. At the very base, the flesh turns into a reddish-black-brown. NH4OH on the cap surface no reaction; the flesh in the cap and stipe changing to deep yellow.
Smell: is very mild, boletoid.
Spores: 14-15(-16) x 5-5.5 µm.
Basidia: 33-51 × 12-14 µm, 2-4-spored.
Cystidia: 40-45 × 8-13 µm.
Habitat: Pure open Quercus garryana stand.

results.notes:
Found on a lawn whose owner said contained a large maple tree, which was cut down a year or two ago. These were growing in almost full sun on old, dead maple roots.

Gilled: light, reddish brown. Plate-like, closely arranged and decurrently attached. Become large and farther apart with age and size.

Spore print: white

Stipe: woody and smooth. Very light brown at younger stages, becoming a very dark, chocolatey brown with age. Somewhat dry and fibrous.

Pileus: light, reddish brown around the edges, mustard-yellowish brown toward the center. Convex at younger stages, becoming flatter with age. Largest diameter about 5.5 inches. Tapers toward the base. No volva or annulus.

Height: tallest at roughly 7 inches.

Grow in large clumps with dozens of stalks emerging from a single point in the soil.

Spores: about 0.5mm, smooth, tear-shaped. No melzer’s reaction.
